default3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIdefaultn the short term the proposed changes to probation could lead to a more fragmented system.default 
defaultWhilst in the long term leveraging the expertise of private and voluntary providers could lead to innovation and improved services, in the short term services may become more fragmented. 
defaultCurrently there is a single provider of probation services for all offenders: the probation trusts. Under the proposed reforms the National Probation Service will continue to serve offenders who pose a high or very high risk of serious harm, with offenders who pose a low or medium risk of serious harm served 
defaultby new rehabilitation providers. Fragmentation will occur when an offender is re-categorised such that responsibility for them moves between providers. 
defaultIn addition, t
defaulthe private and voluntary sector providers that 
defaultwill
default 
defaultdeliver
default these contracts 
defaultmay not
default have
default all
default the pre-existing relationships
default nor the shared responsibility for public protection
default with relevant parties such as Local Authorities or the police
default force
default.
default 
defaultT
defaulthis
